    @Id   // primary key will be automatically provided by Hibernate for each record in table, so I don't need this line here but it should remain same as per best practices.  So make sure your ID matches with the datatype of PK column used by hibernates database tables if not change manually
    @GeneratedValue(strategy=GenerationType.AUTO) // This means that whenever you insert a new User, Hibernate will generate an auto-incremented user id for it (which is primary key in our case).  It follows the strategy of your choice ie AUTO and sequence name can be specified if any
    private long sessionId;   // I used 'long' here as per best practice but you may choose to use int or another appropriate type based on scenario. But remember that auto-incremented values should always fit in a 64 bit integer, else it will result into overflow situation later (unless the ID is set up properly for large datatypes like BigIntegers).
    @Column(name="userId") // Same as above line but I've chosen specific column name rather than using exact same names which are likely to cause conflicts. This follows best practices by not allowing special characters in table or field, and it is set here just for simplicity while following the naming convention of database
    private long userid; 
